05501nam a22008055i 9783111345246DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831113452467 a10.1515/97831113452462doi  a(DE-B1597)665612  a(OCoLC)1416301451  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aMemory and Emotions in Antiquity :bAncient Emotions IV /ced. by George Kazantzidis, Dimos Spatharas. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XXIII, 260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v15800tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction -- tEmotions, Memory, and the Wrath of Achilles: Observations from Cognitive Psychology -- tThe Tension between Memory and Emotion in Homer’s Audience -- tThe Emotional Memories of Internal Narrators: Homer, Virgil, Ovid -- tReligious Emotions and Mnemonic Discourses: The Gold Tablets of Memory -- tRemembering Emotions -- tExploitation of (Alleged) Memories in Demosthenes and Aeschines -- tAristotle on Memory and Emotion in Human and Non-human Animals -- tEmotive Memory Traces in Roman Literature -- tHerodes Atticus, Material Memories, and the Expression and Reception of Grief -- tMemory and Emotion in Philostratus’ Heroicus -- tNostalgia and Reading in Augustine’s Confessions -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex Rerum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributions of this volume discuss the interfaces between memory and emotions in ancient literature, social life, and philosophy. They explore the ways in which memories intersect with emotions in the epics of Homer and Virgil, the importance of memory for the emotions scripts employed by public speakers to enhance the persuasiveness of their arguments, and ‘cultural memory’ in Philostratus’ Heroicus. Contributions that focus on aspects of ancient societies and politics investigate memory and emotions in the Bacchic-Orphic gold leaves, the importance of memories on inscriptions commemorating private and public emotions, and the ways in which emotive memories enhanced the monumentalizing project of Herodes Atticus in Greece. The essays emphasizing philosophical approaches to memory and emotions discuss Aristotle’s biological treatises and Augustine’s deployment of nostalgia and autobiographical narrative in the wider frame of his didactic programme. Modern approaches to embodied cognition are also employed to shed light on how memories attached to our bodily experiences can enhance the interpretation of Roman literature.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAltertum. 4aAltphilologie. 4aGedächtnis. 4aGefühl.  aancient history.  aclassics.  aemotions.  amemory.1 aChaniotis, Angelos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnell, Sophia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevereaux, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownie, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardie, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazantzidis, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMastrangelo, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClay, Mark F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinchin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReady, Jonathan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v